                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d107">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European War 1939/1189: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Finland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schoenfeld</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Helsinki</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-11-26T16:00:00+02:00"
                            >November 26, 1942—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 7:46 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1163. Informant referred to in my 1162, today<note n="63" xml:id="d107fn63">Not
                        printed.</note> says that about month ago Molotov hinted to Swedish
                    representatives that U. S. S. R. might be inclined to discuss cessation of
                    hostilities with Finland and inquired whether Sweden would act as intermediary.
                    Informant says these efforts were fruitless at that time owing to Finnish
                    obstinacy. I have no confirmation of this report from any other source.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schoenfeld</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
